		<a name="top" id="top"></a>
		<div id="siteNotice"><script type='text/javascript'>if (wgNotice != '') document.writeln(wgNotice);</script></div>		<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading">init</h1>
		<div id="bodyContent">
			<h3 id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</h3>
			<div id="contentSub"></div>
									<div id="jump-to-nav">Jump to: <a href="#column-one">navigation</a>, <a href="#searchInput">search</a></div>			<!-- start content -->
			<p><b>init</b> (short for <a href="/wiki/Initialization" title="Initialization"><b>init</b>ialization</a>) is the program on <a href="/wiki/Unix" title="Unix">Unix</a> and <a href="/wiki/Unix-like" title="Unix-like">Unix-like</a> systems that <a href="/wiki/Spawns" title="Spawns" class="mw-redirect">spawns</a> all other processes. It runs as a <a href="/wiki/Daemon_(computer_software)" title="Daemon (computer software)">daemon</a> and typically has <a href="/wiki/Process_identifier" title="Process identifier">PID</a> 1.</p>
<p>The functionality diverged, in Unixes such as <a href="/wiki/Unix_System_III" title="Unix System III" class="mw-redirect">System III</a> and <a href="/wiki/UNIX_System_V" title="UNIX System V">System V</a>, from the functionality provided by the init in <a href="/wiki/Research_Unix" title="Research Unix">Research Unix</a> and its <a href="/wiki/Berkeley_Software_Distribution" title="Berkeley Software Distribution">BSD</a> derivatives. The usage on most <a href="/wiki/Linux_distribution" title="Linux distribution">Linux distributions</a> is compatible with System V, but some distributions, such as <a href="/wiki/Arch_Linux" title="Arch Linux">Arch</a> and <a href="/wiki/Slackware" title="Slackware">Slackware</a>, use a BSD-style and others, such as <a href="/wiki/Gentoo_Linux" title="Gentoo Linux">Gentoo</a>, have their own customized version. Ubuntu<sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1" title=""><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup> and some other Linux distros now use <a href="/wiki/Upstart" title="Upstart">upstart</a><sup id="cite_ref-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-2" title=""><span>[</span>3<span>]</span></a></sup> as a replacement<sup id="cite_ref-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-3" title=""><span>[</span>4<span>]</span></a></sup> for the traditional Init process.</p>
